The paper discusses a neural architecture that models human reading behavior, specifically the skipping of words while still maintaining understanding of the text. This involves an attention module and a task module, which are common components in natural language processing and machine learning. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). Additionally, the paper uses neural networks to model human behavior, which suggests that it could also belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also discusses the optimization of a tradeoff, which is a common theme in optimization and control theory, suggesting that it could belong to cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Finally, the paper uses eye-tracking experiments, which is a common technique in computer vision, suggesting that it could also belong to cs.CV (Computer Vision).
